olive oil
1 sachet mixed sesame seeds
1 apple
1 cucumber
1 sachet teriyaki sauce
½ tbs soy sauce
3 tbs water
1 tsp rice wine vinegar
1 bag salad leaves
1 packet pork loin steaks
1 bag coriander
1 packet garlic aioli
2 Kumara
1 tsp brown sugar

Preheat the oven to 220°C/200°C fan-forced. Peel
the kumara, then cut into fries. Place the fries on
a lined oven tray. Drizzle generously with olive
oil, season with salt and sprinkle with the mixed
sesame seeds. Toss to coat and spread out evenly.
Add a dash of water to the tray, then bake until
tender, 20-25 minutes.

TIP: Leave the kumara unpeeled if you prefer.

While the fries are baking, thinly slice the
cucumber into half-moons. Slice the apple into
thin sticks.

In a small bowl, combine the teriyaki sauce,
brown sugar, soy sauce and the water. Set aside.

In a medium bowl, combine a drizzle of olive
oil and the rice wine vinegar, then season with
salt and pepper. Add the mixed salad leaves,
cucumber and apple. Set aside.

Season the pork loin steaks. Heat a drizzle of olive
oil in a large frying pan over a medium-high heat.
When the oil is hot, cook the pork until cooked
through, 3-4 minutes each side (depending on
thickness). Transfer to a plate. Return the pan to a
medium-high heat, then cook the teriyaki glaze
until reduced slightly, 2-3 minutes. Remove from
the heat, then return the pork to the pan and turn
to coat in the glaze.

TIP: Pork can be served slightly blushing pink in
the centre.

Toss the salad. Roughly chop the coriander. Slice
the teriyaki-glazed pork. Divide the kumara sesame
fries, apple salad and pork between plates. Spoon
over any remaining glaze from the pan and garnish
with the coriander. Serve with the garlic aioli.